      {
        "id": 2950008,
        "name": "William Kelley",
        "username": "William_Kelley",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/william_kelley/{size}/2314_2.png",
        "created_at": "2020-08-04T20:41:31.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-post=\"2\" data-topic=\"163056\">\n<blockquote>\n<p>I was going to say that I was impressed by the airy clusters, but those are quite a few shot berries. Weather-related? Virused? I assume they\u2019ll be eliminated at the sorting table.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Yes, often caused by cooler or wetter weather at flowering - anything that leads to poor fertilization. I left Burgundy a few weeks before flowering but I guess that\u2019s the case here.</p>\n<p>They won\u2019t be eliminated though, it is often thought of as a positive for quality, especially in red\u2026 sometimes the small berries are riper than the rest, sometimes less ripe; but in either case they obviously increase the solid-to-juice ratio.</p>",
        "post_number": 3,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 4,
